<subSubSection id="C31EEBFFBB2BC84C7DFDFF5E2F3BCC89" pageId="6" pageNumber="231" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BBBB874BB2BC84C7DFDFF5E2F3BCC89" blockId="6.[140,1108,166,897]" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB2BC84C7DFDFF5E2A4ACEBD" bold="true" box="[185,312,166,192]" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB2BC84C7DFDFF5E2A41CEBD" box="[185,307,166,192]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231" reason="1">Diagnosis</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Within 
<collectingCountry id="F313F8E4BB2BC84C7CE5FF5F294FCEBC" box="[417,573,167,193]" name="United States of America" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">United States</collectingCountry>
the boldly streaked orange and blackish-gray forewing pattern of 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB2BC84C7C36FF332941CE99" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1905" box="[370,563,202,228]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ferricola">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB2BC84C7C36FF332941CE99" box="[370,563,202,228]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">Hypotrix ferricola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is unmistakable. 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB2BC84C7FBAFF3328CDCE99" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1905" box="[766,959,202,228]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ferricola">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB2BC84C7FBAFF3328CDCE99" box="[766,959,202,228]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">Hypotrix ferricola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB2BC84C7DABFF162923CF75" authority="(Dyar, 1916)" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Dyar" baseAuthorityYear="1916" box="[239,593,237,264]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aselenographa" status="comb. n.">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB2BC84C7DABFF162A77CF7A" box="[239,261,238,263]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB2BC84C7C5CFF152ADECF7A" box="[280,428,237,263]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">aselenographa</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EF95C585BB2BC84C7CFBFF15293ACF75" author="Dyar HG" box="[447,584,237,264]" pageId="6" pageNumber="231" pagination="1 - 37" refId="ref13742" refString="Dyar HG (1916) Descriptions of new Lepidoptera from Mexico. Proceedings of the United States National Museum 51: 1 - 37." type="journal article" year="1916">Dyar, 1916</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A243D91DBB2BC84C7F24FF1529BACF75" box="[608,712,237,264]" pageId="6" pageNumber="231" rank="species">comb. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
[
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB2BC84C7F98FF152BBBCF56" authority="Dyar, 1916" authorityName="Dyar" authorityYear="1916" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Trichorthosia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aselenographa">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB2BC84C7F98FF152F7BCF7A" box="[732,1033,237,263]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">Trichorthosia aselenographa</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EF95C585BB2BC84C7951FF162BBBCF56" author="Dyar HG" pageId="6" pageNumber="231" pagination="1 - 37" refId="ref13742" refString="Dyar HG (1916) Descriptions of new Lepidoptera from Mexico. Proceedings of the United States National Museum 51: 1 - 37." type="journal article" year="1916">Dyar, 1916</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
] from 
<collectingCountry id="F313F8E4BB2BC84C7C5CFEE82A1DCF57" box="[280,367,272,298]" name="Mexico" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">Mexico</collectingCountry>
, except the subterminal line in 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB2BC84C7F93FEE92827CF57" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1905" box="[727,853,272,299]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ferricola">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB2BC84C7F93FEE9299FCF57" box="[727,749,273,298]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB2BC84C7FB9FEE82827CF57" box="[765,853,272,298]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">ferricola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is parallel to the wing margin in the middle part of the wing and then curves outward near the forewing apex (the subterminal line is almost straight to the forewing apex in 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB2BC84C7E2BFEAF2F58CF0C" authorityName="Dyar" authorityYear="1916" box="[879,1066,343,369]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Trichorthosia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aselenographa">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB2BC84C7E2BFEAF28F7CF0D" box="[879,901,343,368]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB2BC84C7ED2FEAF2F58CF0C" box="[918,1066,343,369]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">aselenographa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, so the terminal area is broad mesially and tapered toward each end), and the dark patch in the cell through the reniform and orbicular spots is paler, so the orbicular spot is evident as a dark streak and the reniform spot as a dark crescent (the streak in the cell in 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB2BC84C7DEFFE1C2A14CF80" authorityName="Dyar" authorityYear="1916" box="[171,358,483,510]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Trichorthosia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aselenographa">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB2BC84C7DEFFE1C2BB3CF80" box="[171,193,484,509]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB2BC84C7D96FE1B2A14CF80" box="[210,358,483,509]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">aselenographa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is black, completely obscuring the reniform and orbicular spots). The forewing length in 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB2BC84C7CDDFDFF2965CC5C" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1905" box="[409,535,519,545]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ferricola">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB2BC84C7CDDFDFF2ADDCC5D" box="[409,431,519,544]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB2BC84C7CFBFDFF2965CC5C" box="[447,535,519,545]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">ferricola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is 
<quantity id="4CFC1591BB2BC84C7F7DFDFF29A7CC5C" box="[569,725,518,545]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="1.3" pageId="6" pageNumber="231" unit="mm" value="14.0" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="13.0">13 to 15 mm</quantity>
. The 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB2BC84C7E50FDFF28DCCC5C" box="[788,942,519,545]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">male genitalia</emphasis>
of 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB2BC84C7E91FDFF2F21CC5C" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1905" box="[981,1107,519,545]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ferricola">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB2BC84C7E91FDFF2899CC5D" box="[981,1003,519,544]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB2BC84C7EBFFDFF2F21CC5C" box="[1019,1107,519,545]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">ferricola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have a small, triangular, heavily sclerotized cucullus with a stout seta at the anal angle, a rounded U-shaped notch in the ventral margin of the valve anterior to the cucullus, an apically spatulate uncus, and a long, slender digitus. Th e vesica is very long and narrow with a dense band of spinules on the apical half, a stout rose-thorn spine at the base, and a field of six or seven spike-like cornuti subbasally. In the 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB2BC84C7E0CFD4F2881CCAC" box="[840,1011,695,721]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">female genitalia</emphasis>
the corpus bursae is rounded and the appendix bursae is long and narrow and gently coiled.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C31EEBFFBB2BC84C7DFDFD052AE2CDFC" pageId="6" pageNumber="231" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BBBB874BB2BC84C7DFDFD052AE2CDFC" blockId="6.[140,1108,166,897]" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB2BC84C7DFDFD052A8ACD6A" bold="true" box="[185,504,765,791]" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB2BC84C7DFDFD052A22CD6A" box="[185,336,765,791]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231" reason="1">Distribution</emphasis>
and biology.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB2BC84C7F43FD0629BCCD6A" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1905" box="[519,718,765,791]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ferricola">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB2BC84C7F43FD0629BCCD6A" box="[519,718,765,791]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">Hypotrix ferricola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs in southeastern Arizona, southwestern New 
<collectingRegion id="49C07696BB2BC84C7C2DFCD82AB2CD47" box="[361,448,800,826]" country="Mexico" name="Mexico" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">Mexico</collectingRegion>
, and northern 
<collectingCountry id="F313F8E4BB2BC84C7F34FCD829B5CD47" box="[624,711,800,826]" name="Mexico" pageId="6" pageNumber="231">Mexico</collectingCountry>
. Collecting dates range from early April to early August, possibly representing several generations. Most records are from ponderosa pine forests.
</paragraph>
